\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem concerns distributions as defined in the notes: continuous
 linear functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 from test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is the set of infinitely differentiable functions with compact support
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

 outside some region with finite diameter [differing for different 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

], i.e.
 outside some finite interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 in 1d).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In this part, you will consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\begin{cases}
\ln|x| & x\neq0\\
0 & x=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

 and its (weak) derivative, which is connected to something called the Cauchy
 Principal Value.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 defines a regular distribution, by showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is locally integrable for all intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the 18.01 derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{x} & x\neq0\\
\mbox{undefined} & x=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we just set 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f'(0)=0"$
\end_inset

 at the origin to define 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{x} & x\neq0\\
0 & x=0
\end{cases}$
\end_inset

.
 Show that this 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 locally integrable, and hence does not define a distribution.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

But the weak derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
must
\emph default
 exist, so this means that we have to do something different from the 18.01
 derivative, and moreover 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a regular distribution.
 What is it?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}=\int_{-\infty}^{-\epsilon}\ln(-x)\phi(x)dx+\int_{\epsilon}^{\infty}\ln(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

, since this limit exists and equals 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 from your proof in the previous part.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}-f_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}=\int_{-\epsilon}^{\epsilon}\ln|x|\phi(x)dx\leq(\max\phi)\int_{-\epsilon}^{\epsilon}\ln|x|dx\to0$
\end_inset

, since you should have done the something like the last integral explicitly
 in the previous part.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Compute the distributional derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}=\lim_{\epsilon\to0^{+}}f'_{\epsilon}\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

, and show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 is precisely the 
\emph on
Cauchy Principal Value
\emph default
 (google the definition, e.g.
 on Wikipedia) of the integral of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Alternatively, show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi(x)\}=g\{\phi(x)-\phi(0)\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}g(x)[\phi(x)-\phi(0)]dx$
\end_inset

 (which 
\emph on
is
\emph default
 a well-defined integral for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In class, we only looked explicitly at 1d distributions, but a distribution
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

