\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Show that the distributional gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla f=\delta(\partial V)\left[f_{1}(\vec{x})-f_{2}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})+\begin{cases}
\nabla f_{1}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\in V\\
\nabla f_{2}(\vec{x}) & \vec{x}\notin V
\end{cases},
\]

\end_inset

where the second term is a regular distribution given by the ordinary 18.02
 gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 (assumed to be differentiable), while the first term is the singular distributi
on 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(\partial V)\left[f_{1}(\vec{x})-f_{2}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})\{\phi\}=\oint_{\partial V}\left[f_{1}(\vec{x})-f_{2}(\vec{x})\right]\vec{n}(\vec{x})\phi(\vec{x})d^{d-1}\vec{x}.
\]

\end_inset

 You can use the integral identity that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{V}\nabla\psi d^{d}\vec{x}=\oint_{\partial V}\psi\vec{n}d^{d-1}\vec{x}$
\end_inset

